Think carefully about the problem of "best practice score" design for generated infrastructure artifacts. My system computes a best_practice_score for each generated artifact — Kubernetes manifests, Terraform modules, Helm charts, CICD pipelines. The score is meant to give users immediate feedback on the quality of what was generated and to guide improvements.

What makes a best practice score actually useful versus merely present? Reason through the following failure modes: a score that always returns a high value because the generator controls what it outputs and will naturally generate passing configurations (the generator and scorer are not independent); a score with no normalization that returns different ranges for different artifact types making cross-comparison meaningless; a score that penalizes legitimate advanced configurations (e.g., a Terraform module using count and for_each extensively might trigger complexity penalties even though this is correct HCL); a score that rewards verbosity (more explicit configurations score higher even if some explicitness is unnecessary).

Consider the feedback loop problem: the score is computed at generation time on the generated output. The user has not yet modified anything. Should a generation-time score measure the quality of the generator's default output, or should it be reserved for post-edit validation? These are different use cases with different optimal designs.

Reason through what a well-designed infrastructure artifact quality score should actually measure: completeness (are required fields present?), security (do configurations follow hardening benchmarks?), operability (are there liveness/readiness probes, resource limits, disruption budgets?), maintainability (are names consistent, labels complete, documentation present?). How should these dimensions be weighted, and should the weights be configurable? What prior art exists in code quality scoring (SonarQube's reliability/security/maintainability ratings, CodeClimate's GPA) that can inform this design?
